qas.question: What did GIBAFOR pressure Germany to establish?

context: By 1990, inspired by the fall of the Berlin Wall, <a0_0><b6_0>a pro-democracy movement<b6_0/><a0_0/> arose. Pressure from <a1_0>the United States<a1_0/>, France, and from a group of locally represented countries and agencies called <b5_0>GIBAFOR<b5_0/> (France, the USA, Germany, Japan, the EU, the World Bank, and the UN) finally led Kolingba to agree, in principle, to hold free elections in <a2_0>October 1992<a2_0/> with help from <b7_0>the <a3_0>UN Office of Electoral Affairs<b7_0/><a3_0/>. After <b8_0>using the excuse of <a4_0>alleged irregularities<a4_0/> to suspend the results of the elections<b8_0/> as a pretext for holding on to power, President Kolingba came under intense pressure from GIBAFOR to establish a <b9_0>"Conseil National Politique Provisoire de la République" (Provisional National Political Council, CNPPR) and to set up a "Mixed Electoral Commission"<b9_0/>, which included representatives from all political parties.[citation needed]
